    font-family: verdana;
    font-size: 12px;
    color: #000000;
}
&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;style type="text/css"&gt;&lt;br&gt;
body,td,th {&lt;br&gt;
    font-family: verdana;&lt;br&gt;
    font-size: 12px;&lt;br&gt;
    color: #000000;&lt;br&gt;
}&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/style&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Hello {!Contact.FirstName},&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Thank you for contacting Harman Customer Support.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
There are 3 potential causes for a problem like this.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Broken jack on the source device&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Broken wire&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Broken connector on the headphones&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
First, let’s determine if the source device (Phone, iPad, Computer, etc.) is giving the problem. Please try connecting to a different source using the same wire and headphones. If the problem is resolved, this means that the jack in your phone is no longer working properly. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If the problem is not resolved, switch back to the original device and try the following to see if any of these things change the number of dropouts.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Flex the wire where it joins with the source device. If there is a change in dropouts, this means that the wire is bad. Proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Flex the wire where it joins with the headphones. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Detachable wire:&lt;/b&gt; If there is a change in dropouts, this means that either the wire is bad or the jack in the headphones is failing. Proceed to step 3.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Non-Detachable wire:&lt;/b&gt; If there is a change in dropouts, proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
By making subtle movements, see if you can determine whether the wire or headphone jack is the problem. Should you determine that the wire is the problem, a new wire is necessary. On the other hand, if the headphone jack is the issue, the headphone needs servicing. Proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p style="color: red"&gt;&lt;font size =5&gt;[insert appropriate NEXT STEPS template here]&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/font size&gt;&lt;/font color&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;i&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Note: For your reference, your case number is {!Case.CaseNumber}.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Regards,&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;{!User.FirstName}&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;{!User.Title}&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;The HARMAN Customer Experience Team&lt;/li&gt;

