Hello {!Contact.FirstName},&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Thank you for contacting Harman Customer Support.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
There are 3 potential causes for a problem like this.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Dust/Dirt/Debris blocking the ear tip screen&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Source Device&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Damaged Wire&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Cleaning The Eartips&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p style="margin-left: 40px;"&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This is the most common reason for no sound/lack of sound issues. A simple cleaning will almost always fix this problem. &lt;a href="https://support.jbl.com/us/en/howto/tws-headphones-re-establishing-volume-levels-us/000017775.html"&gt;Please click on this link for detailed online instructions.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
You may also check out these videos for best practices on how to keep your &lt;a href="https://support.jbl.com/us/en/product-support/headphones-support-guide.html#video1"&gt;True Wireless (TWS) headphones&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://support.jbl.com/us/en/product-support/headphones-support-guide.html#video2"&gt;In-Ear headphones&lt;/a&gt; at their best sound performance.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Different Source Device&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p style="margin-left: 40px;"&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If cleaning doesn't solve the issue, we need to determine if the problem is in the device or the headphones. Try to connect the headphones to a different device (phone/tablet/music player) to see if it fixes the problem. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Damaged Wire&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Flex the wire where it joins with the source device. If any sound is heard, this means that the wire is bad. Proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Flex the wire where it joins with the headphones.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Non-Detachable wire:&lt;/b&gt; If any sound is heard, proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Detachable wire:&lt;/b&gt; If any sound is heard, this means that either the wire is bad or the jack in the headphones is failing. Proceed to step 3.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
By making subtle movements, see if you can determine whether the wire or headphone jack is the problem. Should you determine that the wire is the problem, a new wire is necessary. On the other hand, if the headphone jack is the issue, the headphone needs servicing. Proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Reset &lt;br&gt;
&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p style="margin-left: 40px;"&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Reset may fix the issue, much in the way rebooting a computer or phone fixes many problems.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt; RESET will wipe all previous settings and pairings, so it will be necessary to pair your unit with your devices again.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p style="margin-left: 40px;"&gt;&lt;br&gt;
