&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Thank you for contacting Harman Customer Support.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
There are 3 potential causes for a problem like this.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Broken jack on the source device&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Broken wire&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Broken jack on the speaker&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
First, let’s determine if the source device (Phone, iPad, Computer, etc) is causing the problem. Please try connecting to a different source using the same wire and speaker. If the problem is resolved, this means that the jack in your phone is no longer working properly. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If the problem is not resolved, switch back to the original device and try the following to see if any of these things change the number of dropouts. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Flex the wire where it joins with the source device. If there is a change in dropouts, this means that the wire is bad. Proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Flex the wire where it joins with the speaker. If there is a change in dropouts, this means that either the wire is bad or the jack in the speaker is failing. Proceed to step 3.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
By making subtle movements, see if you can determine whether the wire or speaker jack is the problem. Should you determine that the wire is the problem, a new wire is necessary. On the other hand, if the speaker jack is the issue, the speaker needs servicing. Proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;
