&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
There are 4 potential causes for a problem like this.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The sonic quality of your source, depending on what you are listening to&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
EQ Settings&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Source Device&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Tweeter or other components are not functioning properly&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;If the sound is muffled sometimes…&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p style="margin-left: 40px;"&gt;&lt;br&gt;
We need to determine the common denominator. For example, if it only happens on a certain album, you may want to adjust the EQ to boost the treble a little bit while listening to that album. But if it only happens when you are using a specific streaming service or app, you might want to check with the service or app to improve the sonic quality. However, if it appears to be completely random, try boosting the high-frequency settings in the EQ to find a happy medium so that the dullest recordings sound brighter, but the brightest recordings are not too bright. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Please continue to “&lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;” if this does not solve the problem. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;If it is always muffled regardless of the source or song…&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p style="margin-left: 40px;"&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This means that the problem is not with the source material. Please try the following steps in order to determine the problem. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If using an EQ, try turning it off to see if it fixes the problem. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If not using an EQ, try turning it on and boosting the treble a little bit.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
To determine if the problem is in the source device, try connecting the speaker to a different device (phone/tablet/music player/etc.). &lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If 1, 2, or 3 do not fix the issue, this likely means that the internal tweeter or other components are damaged or not working properly. As a last resort, please try resetting the speaker. Reset may fix the issue, much in the way rebooting a computer or phone fixes many problems.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt; RESET will wipe all previous settings and pairings, so it will be necessary to pair your unit with your devices again.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
