&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Thank you for contacting Harman Customer Support.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
There are 4 potential causes for a problem like this.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Broken jack on the source device&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Broken wire&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Broken jack on the speaker&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Speaker needs resetting&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Check to see if the feedback tone is audible when turning the speaker on and off. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;If the feedback tone is not audible, proceed to Step 5 to perform a reset.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;If the feedback tone is audible, proceed to Step 1.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Let’s determine if the source device (Phone, iPad, Computer, etc) is the problem. Please try connecting to a different source using the same wire and speaker. If the problem is resolved, this means that the jack in your device is no longer working properly. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If the problem is not resolved, switch back to the original device and proceed to &lt;b&gt;Step 2&lt;/b&gt;. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Flex the wire where it joins with the source device. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If there is no change in sound, proceed to &lt;b&gt;Step 3&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If there is a change in sound, even if only for a brief moment, this means that the wire needs to be replaced. Proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Flex the wire where it joins with the speaker. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If there is a change in sound, even if only for a brief moment, this means that either the wire is bad or the jack in the speaker is failing. Proceed to &lt;b&gt;Step 4&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If there is no change in sound, proceed to &lt;b&gt;Step 5&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
By making subtle movements, see if you can determine whether the wire or speaker jack is the problem. Should you determine that the wire is the problem, a new wire is necessary. On the other hand, if the speaker jack is the issue, the speaker needs replacing or servicing, depending on your warranty status. Proceed to &lt;b&gt;Next Steps&lt;/b&gt;. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
If the issue is still not resolved, the last thing to try is a reset. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
